ξ 2. neque dubitabant...venturum. This use of non dubito -‘I do not doubt that' with the inf. is scarcely found in Cicero, who always uses quin, unless perhaps in Ep. ad Att. vn. 1, but it is common in Livy.

§3. nondum palamfacto, i. e. qui vivi mortuique essent. Livy often uses the abl. abs. of the past part. without a sub- stantive as permisso, edicto, debellato, in cases where a sentence is taken as the subject to agree with it; but it is a further licence, when it is used as here without any such relation.
